Heavy rainfall in central Mexico has sparked flash floods in Ecatepec and Nezahualcóyotl municipalities, sweeping away vehicles and turning this street into a river.

Local media, citing the director of Civil Protection of Ecatepec, reported that at least two people have died and rescue teams were searching for at least one missing person.

#Mexico #Flooding #BBCNews

node.title: Mexico flash flooding sweeps away cars after heavy rain

node.text:
The restoration of London's Elizabeth Tower, which will cost at least £80 million, is drawing to a close. 

After a delay due to the pandemic, it's now been four years since Big Ben last chimed daily on the hour.

The clock hands will return this month and work will start to remove the scaffolding.

The Taliban's return to power in Afghanistan has left many people, especially in the capital Kabul, with anxiety and fears over the future.

But in more rural areas, which saw some of the fiercest fighting, many others are relieved to see the end of a war that has killed tens of thousands of civilians.

#Afghanistan #BBCNews

node.title: Rural areas of Afghanistan welcome peace and end of war

"Stop for 10 seconds and examine yourself."

Following the death of Girls Aloud star Sarah Harding from breast cancer at the age of 39, Dr Nighat Arif explains the simple breast cancer check people can do themselves. 

She says Covid has put people off trying to see their GP in-person, but you should not hesitate to call your doctor if you find a lump.

#BreastCancer #BBCNews

More countries are now offering teenagers coronavirus vaccines – but not all parents are allowing their children to get immunised.

The US support group Teens for Vaccines - which is run by teenagers for teenagers - says young people around the world are being left out of discussions that affect their own health.

Meanwhile in the UK, vaccine experts recommended on Friday not to give the jab to all 12-15 year olds, although the chief medical officers may take a different approach.

#Covid #Coronavirus #Health #BBCNews

node.title: 'My parents won't let me get the Covid vaccine'

Prof Kim Hyung-suk is a 102-year-old Professor who comes from the same village as the original ‘Great Leader’ of North Korea, Kim Il-Sung. 

In 1945, after Japan was expelled from Korea he had breakfast with the man who would go on to be the first leader of North Korea and the founding father of the Kim dynasty which still holds power to this day.

#BBCNews #NorthKorea

node.title: Breakfast with Kim Il-Sung, North Korea's founding father.

node.text:
Mexico's Supreme Court has ruled that criminal penalties for terminating pregnancies are unconstitutional.

The ruling, for the northern state of Coahuila, prevents women from being prosecuted for getting an abortion. Abortion is currently severely restricted in all but four of the country's states.

A judicial source said the ruling will affect the whole of Mexico, allowing women in states where abortion is criminalised to undergo the procedure with a judge's order.
 
Tap the link in our bio for more on the ruling and how it will affect women across they country.
 
(📷 Getty Images)
 
#Mexico #Abortion #BBCNews

node.text:
Women in Afghanistan have protested against the newly appointed all-male Taliban government.

Hundreds of protesters took to the streets of Kabul to denounce Taliban rule and demand women's rights.

Protesters also chanted anti-Pakistan slogans, as many believe neighbouring Pakistan supports the Taliban, which the country denies.

The Taliban fired warning shots to disperse the crowds and it's been reported that members were taking photos of leading protesters, possibly to help identify them later.

Tap the link in our bio to read more about the Taliban government, which includes those hunted by the American FBI.

(📷 Getty Images)

#Afghanistan #BBCNews

The families of New York City police officers who died helping people during the 9/11 terror attacks 20 years ago have attended the opening of a memorial wall to their relatives.
 
2977 people lost their lives due to the attack when suicide attackers seized US passenger jets and crashed them into two New York skyscrapers. 23 of those were police officers.

Thousands of people were injured or later developed illnesses connected to the attacks, including firefighters who had worked in toxic debris.

It took more than eight months to clean up the site of the fallen Twin Towers, where a museum now stands.

Tap the link in our bio to read more about the September 11 attacks.
 
(📷 Getty Images)
 
#September11 #BBCNews

On the first day El Salvador adopted Bitcoin as legal tender, there were angry protests and tech glitches.  Businesses in the country are now obliged to accept the controversial digital coins as payment, as the government hopes it could save the country $400m a year. 
What wasn't good timing for El Salvador though was the tumble Bitcoin took on its first day as legal tender, falling in value by 20% at one point. 
Some protesters don’t trust the currency, and some accuse the government of not explaining Bitcoin enough.

Tap the link in our bio to read more about the situation in El Salvador.

(📷 Getty Images, EPA) 
#ElSalvador #Bitcoin #BBCNews

node.text:
Britney Spears's father Jamie has filed papers in a Los Angeles court to end the 13-year conservatorship that saw him overseeing her life and finances.

"As Mr Spears has said again and again, all he wants is what is best for his daughter," the filing read.

"If Ms Spears wants to terminate the conservatorship and believes that she can handle her own life, Mr Spears believes that she should get that chance."

It comes two months after the pop star delivered a bombshell testimony to the court, calling for the conservatorship to be terminated immediately.

The singer has sought to remove him from the role twice in the last two years, describing their relationship as “abusive”.

Tap the link in our bio for more on this story.
 
(📸: Getty Images)

#BritneySpears #BBCNews

Heavy rainfall in central Mexico has sparked flash floods in Ecatepec and Nezahualcóyotl municipalities, sweeping away vehicles and turning this street into a river.

Local media, citing the director of Civil Protection of Ecatepec, reported that at least two people have died and rescue teams were searching for at least one missing person.

node.text:
Dragonflies are moving northwards across Britain and Ireland as temperatures rise.

Experts from the British Dragonfly Society say it's an indicator of the effects of climate change.

While some dragonflies and damselflies are expanding their range, others are being driven out of their natural habitats.

Factors such as the use of pesticides, water pollution and habitat loss continue to threaten the health of dragonfly populations within species' existing ranges.

Climate change is affecting many insects with one scientific review of insect numbers in 2019 pointing to 40% of species undergoing "dramatic rates of decline" around the world.

Click the link in our bio to learn more about how dragonflies and damselflies are moving north.

📷 (Dave Smallshire, Iain Leach, Pam Taylor, Chris Giles/BBC)

#Insects #Dragonflies #ClimateChange #BBCNews

The restoration of London's Elizabeth Tower, which will cost at least £80 million, is drawing to a close. 

After a delay due to the pandemic, it's now been four years since Big Ben last chimed daily on the hour.

The clock hands will return this month and work will start to remove the scaffolding.

node.text:
Kim Kardashian, and other influencers, have been criticised for promoting cryptocurrency on social media.

The head of the UK’s Financial Conduct Authority, Charles Randell, said they are fuelling the "delusions of quick riches".

He said Ms Kardashian’s sponsored post, to her 251 million Instagram followers, advertised a product he called "a speculative digital token created a month before by unknown developers".

Although unable to say if the product was a scam, he warned that “social media influencers are routinely paid by scammers to help them pump and dump new tokens on the back of pure speculation.”

Tap the link in bio to read more about the risks of buying cryptocurrency.

(📷 Getty Images)

node.text:
A blue plaque remembering Muppets creator Jim Henson has been installed at his former home in London.

He moved to the UK to make The Muppet Show, starring Kermit the Frog and Miss Piggy, which was a huge hit in the 1970s and 1980s.

English Heritage unveiled the plaque ahead of what would have been Jim Henson's 85th birthday.

His son, Brian, said "It's an honour to have his British home recognised with a blue plaque, knowing that he so admired and respected the talent in London."

Tap the link in bio to read more about Jim Henson’s work.

(📷 Getty Images, English Heritage, The Jim Henson Company)

#TheMuppets #JimHenson #BBCNews

node.text:
American actor Michael K Williams, best known for starring in HBO drama series The Wire, has been found dead in his New York apartment. 

Williams began his career as a dancer and performed with Madonna and George Michael before moving into acting, where he was nominated for three Emmy Awards.

Pictured in 2003 at the premiere of The Wire, he played Omar Little, a gay, streetwise robber of drug gangs.

His cause of death has not yet been officially confirmed. However, US media quote law enforcement sources as saying he died from a suspected drug overdose, an addiction problem he had previously openly discussed over the years.

Tap the link in bio to read more about the tributes to the actor Michael K Williams.
